# Page Layout & Scaling

The entire site uses **proportional outer padding** that scales with the viewport. The whole composition (header, footer, all page sections) is built around the designer's 1920px reference, and we keep the same proportions at every screen width.

## The Rule

- **Outer page padding:** `5.625vw` on the left and right of every page section.
  - At 1920px → 108px (matches designer's spec)
  - At 1024px → 57.6px
  - At 390px → 21.9px
- **6-column grid** with **5px gutter** for any layout that explicitly maps to the designer's 6-col system.
- **No `max-width` constraint** on outer containers. The `5.625vw` padding alone keeps the layout proportional; capping the width breaks scaling on different screens.

## How to Apply It

**Tailwind class (preferred for one-off sections):**

```tsx
<section className="px-[5.625vw]">…</section>
```

**Shared `Container` component (use for any page that needs a wrapper):**

```tsx
import Container from "@/components/Container";

<Container>…</Container>
```

`Container` already applies `w-full px-[5.625vw]` and is the default wrapper for inner pages (About, Contact, Work, Case Studies, Insights, Branded Stories, etc.).

**CSS variable (use in `globals.css` or any raw CSS):**

```css
.my-element {
  padding-left: var(--page-padding);
  padding-right: var(--page-padding);
}
```

The variable `--page-padding` is defined in `src/app/globals.css` and equals `5.625vw`.

## Don't Do This

```tsx
// ❌ Don't hardcode fixed pixel outer padding — it breaks the proportional system.
<section className="px-[20px] md:px-[40px]">…</section>

// ❌ Don't wrap outer containers in max-width — it creates large empty gaps on
//    big screens and shrinks the composition on smaller ones.
<div className="mx-auto max-w-[1704px]">…</div>

// ❌ Don't introduce new breakpoint-based padding for outer containers.
<section className="px-4 sm:px-6 md:px-8 lg:px-12">…</section>
```

Component-internal padding (button padding, badge padding, card padding) can still use any fixed values — the rule only applies to **outer page padding** (the gap between content and the viewport edge).

## Typography

Page-level body and heading text should use `clamp()` to scale with viewport while staying readable on small screens. Examples currently in use:

- Lorem-style hero text: `clamp(1.8rem, 4vw, 60px)`
- Section secondary text: `clamp(1.125rem, 2vw, 38px)`
- Section headings: `clamp(2.5rem, 2.5vw, 4rem)`

These already scale proportionally up to the 1920px reference, then cap to keep the design system consistent on ultra-wide displays.
